Following is the text of
 Canada â€™s leading indicators report from  Statistics Canada .  The composite leading index rose 0.6% in February, following
a 0.4% gain in January. This was the eighth consecutive monthly
increase of the index. In February, 6 of the 10 components rose.  Composite leading indicator  The financial components had the largest gains in the month,
with the stock market recovering after eight monthly declines
and the money supply component continuing to expand. As well,
manufacturing was supported by an increase in new orders and the
ratio of inventories to sales rose for the fourth consecutive
month. Household demand for durable goods also rose, supported
by auto sales. The US leading indicator rose as a result of
increases in US financial indicators and manufacturing.  The housing component edged down following five monthly gains.
Sales of furniture and appliances were also down. Services
employment was unchanged and the average workweek was stable
after four consecutive increases.  To contact the reporter on this story:
